{"id":385,"date":"2022-02-15T03:11:34","date_gmt":"2022-02-15T03:11:34","guid":{"rendered":"https:\/\/research.dwi.ufl.edu\/projects\/digitalepigraphy.org\/?post_type=product&#038;p=385"},"modified":"2022-09-28T15:59:53","modified_gmt":"2022-09-28T15:59:53","slug":"shape-from-shading-3d-reconstruction-tool","status":"publish","type":"product","link":"https:\/\/www.digitalepigraphy.org\/page\/shape-from-shading-3d-reconstruction-tool\/","title":{"rendered":"Shape-From-Shading 3D reconstruction On-Line Tool"},"content":{"rendered":"<p><iframe loading=\"lazy\" src=\"https:\/\/www.youtube.com\/embed\/QHJakpu4P6A?feature=oembed\" width=\"1200\" height=\"600\" frameborder=\"0\" allowfullscreen=\"allowfullscreen\"><\/iframe><\/p>\n<p>BERLIN, Germany<br \/>\nFebruary 15, 2022<\/p>\n<p>Our interdisciplinary team is happy to present today in Berlin&#8217;s Digital Classicist Seminar series the new on-line tool for 3D reconstruction of epigraphic squeezes using our shape-from-shading technique (<a href=\"https:\/\/research.dwi.ufl.edu\/projects\/digitalepigraphy.org\/page\/a-novel-framework-for-3d-reconstruction-and-analysis-of-ancient-inscriptions-2\/\">MVA 2010<\/a>). The new tool that replaces our older Digital Epigraphy Toolbox can be accessed in the following address:<\/p>\n<p><a href=\"https:\/\/www.digitalepigraphy.org\/db\/app\/sfs\">https:\/\/www.digitalepigraphy.org\/db\/app\/sfs<\/a><\/p>\n<p>The new on-line tool utilizes cloud technology to store, process, and disseminate the results of the 3D reconstruction algorithm. It allows the users to upload pictures of a flat inscribed object (such as epigraphic squeeze, paper embossment, seal, inscriptions, casts of coins, and others), taken from the same perspective using 2 or 4 different lighting conditions.<\/p>\n<p><img loading=\"lazy\" decoding=\"async\" class=\"alignnone wp-image-389 aligncenter\" src=\"https:\/\/research.dwi.ufl.edu\/projects\/digitalepigraphy.org\/wp-content\/uploads\/2022\/03\/sfs_screenshot2-300x222.jpg\" alt=\"\" width=\"523\" height=\"387\" srcset=\"https:\/\/www.digitalepigraphy.org\/wp-content\/uploads\/2022\/03\/sfs_screenshot2-300x222.jpg 300w, https:\/\/www.digitalepigraphy.org\/wp-content\/uploads\/2022\/03\/sfs_screenshot2-1024x758.jpg 1024w, https:\/\/www.digitalepigraphy.org\/wp-content\/uploads\/2022\/03\/sfs_screenshot2-768x568.jpg 768w, https:\/\/www.digitalepigraphy.org\/wp-content\/uploads\/2022\/03\/sfs_screenshot2-600x444.jpg 600w, https:\/\/www.digitalepigraphy.org\/wp-content\/uploads\/2022\/03\/sfs_screenshot2.jpg 1308w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 523px) 100vw, 523px\" \/><\/p>\n<p>The users then, can process the photos and produce the heightmap and normal map of the depicted surface.<\/p>\n<p><img loading=\"lazy\" decoding=\"async\" class=\"alignnone wp-image-388 aligncenter\" src=\"https:\/\/research.dwi.ufl.edu\/projects\/digitalepigraphy.org\/wp-content\/uploads\/2022\/03\/sfs_screenshot3-300x222.jpg\" alt=\"\" width=\"528\" height=\"391\" srcset=\"https:\/\/www.digitalepigraphy.org\/wp-content\/uploads\/2022\/03\/sfs_screenshot3-300x222.jpg 300w, https:\/\/www.digitalepigraphy.org\/wp-content\/uploads\/2022\/03\/sfs_screenshot3-1024x758.jpg 1024w, https:\/\/www.digitalepigraphy.org\/wp-content\/uploads\/2022\/03\/sfs_screenshot3-768x568.jpg 768w, https:\/\/www.digitalepigraphy.org\/wp-content\/uploads\/2022\/03\/sfs_screenshot3-600x444.jpg 600w, https:\/\/www.digitalepigraphy.org\/wp-content\/uploads\/2022\/03\/sfs_screenshot3.jpg 1311w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 528px) 100vw, 528px\" \/><\/p>\n<p>A variety of sample projects is provided to help you familiarize yourself with the features and options of the software.<\/p>\n<p><img loading=\"lazy\" decoding=\"async\" class=\" wp-image-387 aligncenter\" src=\"https:\/\/research.dwi.ufl.edu\/projects\/digitalepigraphy.org\/wp-content\/uploads\/2022\/03\/sfs_screenshot4-300x222.jpg\" alt=\"\" width=\"522\" height=\"386\" srcset=\"https:\/\/www.digitalepigraphy.org\/wp-content\/uploads\/2022\/03\/sfs_screenshot4-300x222.jpg 300w, https:\/\/www.digitalepigraphy.org\/wp-content\/uploads\/2022\/03\/sfs_screenshot4-1024x759.jpg 1024w, https:\/\/www.digitalepigraphy.org\/wp-content\/uploads\/2022\/03\/sfs_screenshot4-768x569.jpg 768w, https:\/\/www.digitalepigraphy.org\/wp-content\/uploads\/2022\/03\/sfs_screenshot4-600x444.jpg 600w, https:\/\/www.digitalepigraphy.org\/wp-content\/uploads\/2022\/03\/sfs_screenshot4.jpg 1308w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 522px) 100vw, 522px\" \/><\/p>\n<p>The software is open-source and the source code can be accessed within the application from the menu About &gt; For Developers &gt; Source Code<\/p>\n","protected":false},"excerpt":{"rendered":"<p>BERLIN, Germany February 15, 2022 Our interdisciplinary team is happy to present today in Berlin&#8217;s Digital Classicist Seminar series the new on-line tool for 3D reconstruction of epigraphic squeezes using our shape-from-shading technique (MVA 2010). The new tool that replaces our older Digital Epigraphy Toolbox can be accessed in the following address: https:\/\/www.digitalepigraphy.org\/db\/app\/sfs The new<span class=\"read-more-faq\"><a href=\"https:\/\/www.digitalepigraphy.org\/page\/shape-from-shading-3d-reconstruction-tool\/\">Read More<\/a><\/span><\/p>\n","protected":false},"featured_media":386,"comment_status":"closed","ping_status":"closed","template":"","meta":[],"_links":{"self":[{"href":"https:\/\/www.digitalepigraphy.org\/wp-json\/wp\/v2\/product\/385"}],"collection":[{"href":"https:\/\/www.digitalepigraphy.org\/wp-json\/wp\/v2\/product"}],"about":[{"href":"https:\/\/www.digitalepigraphy.org\/wp-json\/wp\/v2\/types\/product"}],"replies":[{"embeddable":true,"href":"https:\/\/www.digitalepigraphy.org\/wp-json\/wp\/v2\/comments?post=385"}],"wp:featuredmedia":[{"embeddable":true,"href":"https:\/\/www.digitalepigraphy.org\/wp-json\/wp\/v2\/media\/386"}],"wp:attachment":[{"href":"https:\/\/www.digitalepigraphy.org\/wp-json\/wp\/v2\/media?parent=385"}],"curies":[{"name":"wp","href"